# 06 - Engine

## Purpose

This document describes the conceptual design of the Nyx protection engine.

It explains the responsibilities of the engine, its execution lifecycle, and the relationship between its internal components.

Implementation details are intentionally excluded.

---

# Overview

The engine is the core component of Nyx.

It is responsible for transforming developer-defined protection configurations into executable protection operations.

All protection behavior originates from the engine.

---

# Engine Responsibilities

The engine is responsible for:

* Loading protection configuration
* Validating configuration
* Planning protection execution
* Coordinating protection capabilities
* Executing protection operations
* Producing protection results

The engine does not provide user interfaces.

---

# Execution Lifecycle

Every protection request follows the same conceptual lifecycle.

```text id="k1a8cf"
Configuration
      │
      ▼
Validation
      │
      ▼
Planning
      │
      ▼
Execution
      │
      ▼
Results
```

Each stage has a single responsibility.

---

# Validation

Validation ensures that a protection request is complete and internally consistent before execution begins.

Validation may include:

* configuration correctness
* capability compatibility
* parameter validation
* dependency checks

Execution should never begin if validation fails.

---

# Planning

Planning converts validated configuration into an executable protection plan.

The planner determines:

* which capabilities are executed
* execution order
* required dependencies
* execution context

Planning is deterministic.

The same inputs should produce the same execution plan.

---

# Execution

Execution applies the planned protection operations.

The engine coordinates capabilities while ensuring:

* deterministic execution
* isolation between capabilities
* predictable behavior

Capabilities should not coordinate themselves.

The engine performs orchestration.

---

# Results

Execution produces structured results.

Examples include:

* successful completion
* warnings
* validation failures
* execution failures
* generated artifacts

Results should be machine-readable whenever possible.

---

# Engine Boundaries

The engine does not:

* implement editor integrations
* manage user interfaces
* depend on IDEs
* depend on build systems
* depend on automation platforms

External systems interact with the engine through stable public interfaces.

---

# Determinism

Whenever deterministic configuration is used, identical inputs should produce identical protection results.

Deterministic behavior is important for:

* debugging
* testing
* collaboration
* CI/CD
* reproducible builds

---

# Extensibility

The engine should remain open for new protection capabilities without requiring architectural redesign.

Adding new capabilities should extend the engine rather than modify its core responsibilities.

---

# Summary

The engine coordinates the complete protection lifecycle.

It validates requests, plans execution, orchestrates protection capabilities, and produces deterministic protection results while remaining independent of external integrations.
